101.subject: CLEN
101.courseDescription: Engineering Approaches to Problems. (3-0). Credit 3. Basic characteristics of the engineering profession and the process by which technology is developed for real application; engineering thinking and problem-solving processes; common engineering concepts; engineering disciplines and project types.

181.subject: CLEN
181.courseDescription: Engineering Learning Community & Student Success Seminar. Credit 0 to 1. Welcoming seminar to the college of engineering to assist with transition to college; includes introduction to engineering majors, college and university resources; topics evolve as students advance through the engineering curriculum. Prerequisite: Must be enrolled in the College of Engineering; also taught at Galveston and Qatar campuses.

201.subject: CLEN
201.courseDescription: Tools for Engineering Analysis. (2-2). Credit 3. Introduction to prominent categories of engineering quantitative analysis; pattern finding in data; optimization; prediction of future states; modeling of physical systems; laboratory exercises to use computational tools as means of implementing mathematical concepts. Prerequisites: CLEN 101; MATH 131, MATH 142, MATH 147, MATH 151, or MATH 171.

289.subject: CLEN
289.courseDescription: Special Topics In... Credit 0 to 4. Selected topics in an identified area of engineering.

301.subject: CLEN
301.courseDescription: Humanity and Materials. (3-0). Credit 3. Engineering processes for obtaining, shaping, fabricating and manufacturing materials for human use; changes in materials development and application through human history; important materials in contemporary society and their properties; emerging and future materials. Prerequisite: CLEN 201.

302.subject: CLEN
302.courseDescription: Survey of Nuclear Technology. (3-0). Credit 3. Overview of important discoveries in atomic and nuclear physics in 20th and 21st Centuries; basics of atomic and nuclear physics; radiation and its impact; nuclear reactors, fuel cycle, waste disposal and associated policy issues; nuclear safety, safeguards and security; applications of nuclear technology. Prerequisite: CLEN 201.

303.subject: CLEN
303.courseDescription: Renewable Energy and the Environment. (3-0). Credit 3. Overview of important renewable energy sources for human societies; role of thermodynamic principles in design of systems for capturing, storing, converting, delivering, and conserving energy; solar, wind, bioenergy, water, and geothermal energy sources; environmental effects of various energy sources; basic economics of energy systems. Prerequisite: CLEN 201.

304.subject: CLEN
304.courseDescription: Pushing the Limits of Construction - Taller, Stronger, Leaner. (3-0). Credit 3. Case studies in ambitious construction projects in contemporary society; project magnitude, unique challenges, environmental impact and innovations present in each case study; illustration of elementary structural design principles and life cycle cost analysis. Prerequisite: CLEN 201.

689.subject: CLEN
689.courseDescription: Special Topics in... Credit 1 to 4.  Selected topics in an identified area of engineering. May be repeated for credit. Prerequisite: Graduate classification.
